net.objectof.model

Enum Stereotype

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<Stereotype>
      • net.objectof.model.Stereotype
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<Stereotype>

    public enum Stereotype
extends java.lang.Enum<Stereotype>
    Stereotypes define the elemental types. Stereotypes define concrete intent rather than implementation: they categorize data with implicit or assumed attributes / behaviors. Stereotypes, by themselves, are not within a class hierarchy and are independent value domains.

    Stereotypes are used to categorize types, specifically a Kind.

    Each Stereotype is documented below with:

    • assume: The assumed Java type in the absence of a specific contract.
    • json: The relationship to the Stereotype and JSON types.
    Author:
    jdh

      • MAPPED

      • INDEXED

      • BOOL

        public static final Stereotype BOOL
        A two-state value, generally implemented as a boolean.

        When implementing from data potentially holding more than two states: "false" is to be implemented as "off/zero/null" with "true" being !false (not false). Generally a falsehood has better semantics than a truth.

      • COMPOSED

        public static final Stereotype COMPOSED
        Any tuple/structure, record (which is defined here as a tuple whose elements are mapped rather than indexed), or object. A Composed entries are fixed and set by the type.

        Use COMPOSED for classes that are "opaque" to the model, such as an implementation class that needs to be referenced but not otherwise modeled.

      • REF

        public static final Stereotype REF
        A reference to an entity. An entity is defined here as any "whole" data structure rather than a part of an aggregation. The model supports the distinction (even though, for example, Java doesn't). As an example, consider a JSON document: The document is-a entity. Parts of the entity are included in the document itself while referenced Entities are referenced in some form (through a string or reference-style JSON object).

      • FN

        public static final Stereotype FN
        A function or functional object; a method; a web service.

      • SET

        public static final Stereotype SET
        A Set.

      • MOMENT

        public static final Stereotype MOMENT
        A time based value reporting a UTC minute. Implementations using a "Unix/Java long" MUST truncate or otherwise ignore sub-minute values. To provide a sub-minute point in time, define an (INT|NUM) to capture the desired precision.

      • MEDIA

        public static final Stereotype MEDIA
        Media represents an "opaque object" nominally consisting of a sequence of octets/bytes. Use Media only for true media types or an implementation-dependent class that requires state transfer (serialization) but should not otherwise be modeled as empty composites.
